<tool_priority>
Choose tools based on whether the target requires authentication:

── UNAUTHENTICATED endpoints ────────────────────────────────────────────────
1. terminal_execute  ← curl/httpx for raw HTTP, nmap, nuclei, ffuf
   Examples:
   - SSRF:    curl -s 'https://target/api/validate-url?url=http://169.254.169.254/'
   - Headers: curl -si https://target/ | head -30

2. execute_skill ← pre-built scanners (XSS, dir brute, etc.)

── AUTHENTICATED endpoints (PREFERRED workflow) ─────────────────────────────
When the target requires login, or you already have a browser session:

1. browser_action ← PRIMARY tool. Stay in the browser for ALL steps:

   STEP A — Login once, then STAY in the browser:
   - Navigate to login page
   - execute_js to fill credentials and submit
   - You now have a live authenticated session

   STEP B — Intercept real API calls via execute_js:
   Inject this at the start of any page to capture all requests:
   ```
   window.__requests = [];
   const orig = window.fetch;
   window.fetch = async (...a) => { window.__requests.push({type:'fetch', url: a[0], opts: a[1]}); return orig(...a); };
   const origXHR = window.XMLHttpRequest.prototype.open;
   window.XMLHttpRequest.prototype.open = function(m,u) { window.__requests.push({type:'xhr',method:m,url:u}); return origXHR.apply(this,arguments); };
   ```
   Then navigate to the feature and run: `return JSON.stringify(window.__requests);`

   STEP C — Test SSRF/IDOR by replaying captured requests:
   - Use execute_js to call fetch() with modified parameters directly in the browser
   - This keeps session cookies automatically — no need to extract tokens
   Example for SSRF test:
   ```
   const r = await fetch('/api/validate-url', {method:'POST', headers:{'Content-Type':'application/json'},
     body: JSON.stringify({url: 'http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/'})});
   return await r.text();
   ```
   Example for IDOR test:
   ```
   const r = await fetch('/api/users/2', {headers: {'Accept': 'application/json'}});
   return {status: r.status, body: await r.text()};
   ```

   STEP D — Validate and note evidence:
   - Check response status + body in the return value
   - If confirmed: take a screenshot then call create_vulnerability_report

── GENERAL RULES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
❌ NEVER switch from browser to curl after logging in — you lose the session.
❌ NEVER write Python scripts that send HTTP requests. Use browser fetch() or curl.
❌ NEVER use python_action.
✅ For curl that needs session cookies, export cookies first:
   `document.cookie` → use `-H 'Cookie: ...'` in curl (last resort only).
</tool_priority>

